      "\n   `d/dt [f((1-t)x + ty)] = ∑_i (y_i - x_i) (∂f/∂x_i)((1-t)x + ty)`.\n\n2. To find the second derivative, differentiate again with respect to `t`:  \n   `d²/dt² [f((1-t)x + ty)] = d/dt [∑_i (y_i - x_i) (∂f/∂x_i)((1-t)x + ty)]`  \n   `= ∑_i (y_i - x_i) d/dt [(∂f/∂x_i)((1-t)x + ty)]`  \n   For each `i`, by the chain rule:  \n   `d/dt [(∂f/∂x_i)((1-t)x + ty)] = ∑_j (d/dt [(1-t)x_j + ty_j]) (∂/∂x_j)[(∂f/∂x_i)]((1-t)x + ty)`  \n   `= ∑_j (y_j - x_j) (∂²f/∂x_j∂x_i)((1-t)x + ty)`.  \n\n   Therefore, the second derivative becomes:  \n   `∑_i (y_i - x_i) ∑_j (y_j - x_j) (∂²f/∂x_j∂x_i)((1-t)x + ty)`  \n   `= ∑_i ∑_j (y_i - x_i)(y_j - x_j) (∂²f/∂x_j∂x_i)((1-t)x +",
      "\n  have h₁ : deriv (interpolated_deriv x y f) = interpolated_deriv2 x y f := by\n    -- Compute the derivative of the interpolated derivative\n    have h₂ : deriv (interpolated_deriv x y f) = fun t : ℝ => ∑ i : Fin n, ∑ j : Fin n, (y i - x i) * (y j - x j) * (nth_partial i (nth_partial j f)) ((1 - t) • x + t • y) := by\n      -- Use the fact that the derivative of the interpolated derivative is the second derivative\n      funext t\n      simp [interpolated_deriv, interpolated, interpolator, E]\n      -- Use the chain rule and properties of partial derivatives to simplify the expression\n      <;>\n        simp_all [deriv_const, deriv_add, deriv_smul, deriv_id, mul_comm, mul_assoc, mul_left_comm]\n      <;>\n        norm_num\n      <;>\n        ring_nf\n      <;>\n        field_simp [Finset.sum_add_distrib, Finset.mul_sum]\n      <;>\n        simp_all [Finset.sum_add_distrib, Finset.mul_sum]\n      <;>\n        norm_num\n      <;>\n        linarith\n    -- Use the result to conclude the proof\n    rw [h₂]\n    <;>\n      simp_all [interpolated_deriv2]\n    <;>\n      rfl\n  exact h₁",
